{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17637080","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17637080"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T18:37:45+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T18:37:45+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17627"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17627","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17627"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.18,0.09,0.41,0.27,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10341"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71815"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10341","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10341"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17627"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57304"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10032"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24190"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24199"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24249"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71815","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/71815"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EPeristaltic and segmental activity is an essential part of the digestive process.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes segmentation in the small intestine?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Coordinated waves of longitudinal muscle contraction","Peristaltic waves moving contents distally","Rhythmic contraction and relaxation of circular muscle","Simultaneous contraction of circular and longitudinal muscle","Tonic contraction of the entire intestinal segment"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERhythmic contraction and relaxation of circular muscle\u003C/strong\u003E is the defining characteristic of segmentation in the small intestine. This creates alternating constricted and relaxed segments that effectively mix intestinal contents with digestive enzymes and push them against the mucosa for absorption.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECoordinated waves of longitudinal muscle contraction\u003C/strong\u003E - This pattern would primarily change intestinal length rather than mix contents\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESimultaneous contraction of circular and longitudinal muscle\u003C/strong\u003E - This would create rigid segments without the mixing action\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPeristaltic waves moving contents distally\u003C/strong\u003E - While peristalsis does occur in the small intestine, it is distinct from segmentation and primarily moves contents forward\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETonic contraction of the entire intestinal segment\u003C/strong\u003E - This would prevent the alternating pattern needed for mixing\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESegmentation contractions occur most frequently in the duodenum (12 per minute) and decrease in frequency towards the ileum (8 per minute), allowing appropriate time for digestion and absorption.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Segmentation contractions in the small intestine chop and mix intestinal contents with digestive enzymes.","Segmentation occurs through alternating contraction and relaxation of circular smooth muscle.","The frequency of segmentation contractions is highest in the duodenum and decreases towards the ileum."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57304"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17627"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57304","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/57304"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-20T16:22:00+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-20T16:22:23+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10341"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71815"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4928","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4928"},"attributes":{"